Reserve Nathan Watson hit a 3-pointer with
four seconds left to lift Auburn to a 56-54 victory over LSU on
Saturday.
article.headline: Reserve Watson delivers winning 3-pointer for LSU
article.linkText: Watson's late 3-pointer helps Auburn sink LSU
article.story:
AUBURN, Ala. (AP) -- Reserve Nathan Watson hit a 3-pointer with
four seconds left to lift Auburn to a 56-54 victory over LSU on
Saturday.

	   The host Tigers (17-5, 6-3 Southeastern Conference) led all the
way until Jaime Lloreda's basket with 3:07 left gave LSU (13-8,
2-7) a 54-53 lead.

	   Neither team scored for the next three minutes. Lloreda missed
the first free throw of a 1-and-1 situation with 19 seconds left,
with Auburn's Marco Killingsworth collecting the rebound.

	   Auburn called a timeout with 13 seconds left, then Marquis
Daniels fired a pass to an open Watson on the left wing for the
game-winner. Watson, a walk-on who has become a key player off the
bench, had missed his first four shots, including three 3-pointers, but didn't hesitate to put up another one.

	   Antonio Hudson's 3-pointer at the buzzer fell short as Auburn
maintained its surprising lead in the Western Division.

	   Daniels finished with 15 points, five steals and four assists
and Derrick Bird scored 14, including four first-half 3-pointers,
for Auburn. Killingsworth had nine points and a career-high 12
rebounds.

	   Ronald Dupree led LSU with 17 points and seven rebounds on
8-of-12 shooting but had five turnovers.

	   Auburn, the league's best shooting team, shot just 38 percent
and made 7-of-14 free throws but still has won all four games
against SEC West opponents.

	   Bird's 3-pointer with four seconds left in the first half gave
Auburn a 32-26 lead, built mostly on opportunistic defense.

	   The host Tigers swiped three inbounds passes in a span of less
than three minutes -- getting a fourth in the second half -- and had
nine steals, taking a 22-9 lead on a Marco Killingsworth steal and
basket.

	   Dupree hit three straight jump shots, including a 3-pointer,
then his layup cut it to three with 39 seconds left before Bird's
fourth 3-pointer.
